<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="529" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,392]" pageId="14" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,223,248]" pageId="14" pageNumber="529">Remarks.</emphasis>
Introduced species. We speculate that this species was introduced at least two or three decades ago, long enough for the rural communities to endow it with the unique vernacular name “Pimpin.” Since there are many aquaculture farms breeding carps of Chinese origin in 
<collectingRegion box="[798,865,295,320]" country="Malaysia" name="Perak" pageId="14" pageNumber="529">Perak</collectingRegion>
, we speculate that the species may have arrived together with the Chinese carps unintentionally in the form of stowaway fry. Specimens we encountered were identified following 
<bibRefCitation author="Nichols, J. T." box="[381,550,367,392]" pageId="14" pageNumber="529" refId="ref17751" refString="Nichols, J. T. (1943) Fresh-Water Fishes of China. The American Museum of Natural History, New York." type="book" year="1943">Nichols (1943)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Lim, K. K. &amp; Kwik, J. T. B." box="[604,834,367,392]" pageId="14" pageNumber="529" pagination="271 - 273" refId="ref16488" refString="Lim, K. K. P &amp; Kwik, J. T. B. (2012) New record of the Chinese Cyprinid fish Toxobramis Houdemeri in Singapore. Nature in Singapore, 5, 271 - 273." type="journal article" year="2012">Lim &amp; Kwik (2012)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
